The problem requires a lower bound for \(P(|Y / n - 0.25| < 0.05)\) when \(Y \sim b(n, 0.25)\) and \(n = 500\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality, for a random variable with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), \(P(|X - \mu| \geq d) \leq \sigma^2 / d^2\), so \(P(|X - \mu| < d) \geq 1 - \sigma^2 / d^2\).

Here, \(X = Y / n\), \(\mu = p = 0.25\), \(d = 0.05\), and the variance of \(Y / n\) is \(\sigma^2 = p(1-p)/n\).

Calculate \(\sigma^2\):  
