The problem requires approximating \(P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) where \(\bar{X}\) is the sample mean of a random sample of size 12 from a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\).

The uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = 1/12\). The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) has mean \(\mu_{\bar{X}} = \mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma_{\bar{X}}^2 = \sigma^2 / n = (1/12)/12 = 1/144\), so the standard deviation is \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = 1/12\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed for \(n = 12\). Standardize the probability:
\[
P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3) = P\left( \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} \leq \frac{\bar{X} - 0.5}{1/12} \leq \frac{2/3 - 0.5}{1/12} \right) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2),
\]
where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable, and \( (2/3 - 0.5) / (1/12) = (1/6) / (1/12) = 2 \).

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = \Phi(2) - \Phi(0)\), where \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\) and \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.97725\). Thus,
\[
P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = 0.97725 - 0.5 = 0.47725.
