Problem: 5.4-21. Let $X$ and $Y$ be independent with distributions $N(5,16)$ and $N(6,9)$, respectively. Evaluate $P(X>Y)=$ $P(X-Y>0)$.
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent with \(X \sim N(5, 16)\) and \(Y \sim N(6, 9)\). The probability \(P(X > Y)\) is equivalent to \(P(X - Y > 0)\). Define \(D = X - Y\). Since \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent normal random variables, \(D\) follows a normal distribution with mean \(\mu_D = \mu_X - \mu_Y = 5 - 6 = -1\) and variance \(\sigma_D^2 = \sigma_X^2 + \sigma_Y^2 = 16 + 9 = 25\), so \(D \sim N(-1, 25)\).

The probability \(P(D > 0)\) is found by standardizing \(D\) to a standard normal variable. The standardized value is:
\[
Z = \frac{D - \mu_D}{\sigma_D} = \frac{D - (-1)}{5}
\]
Thus,
\[
P(D > 0) = P\left(Z > \frac{0 - (-1)}{5}\right) = P\left(Z > \frac{1}{5}\right) = P(Z > 0.2)
\]
Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z < 0.2)\). The cumulative distribution function value is \(P(Z < 0.2) \approx 0.5793\), so:
\[
P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207
\]
Rounding to three decimal places gives 0.421.

